# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: disruption-of-1843
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] An **act of parliament**, as a form of primary legislation, is a text of law passed by the legislative body of a jurisdiction (often a parliament or council).
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] In most countries with a parliamentary system of government, acts of parliament begin as a bill, which the legislature votes on.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Depending on the structure of government, this text may then be subject to assent or approval from the executive branch.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] A draft act of parliament is known as a bill.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] In other words, a bill is a proposed law that needs to be discussed in the parliament before it can become a law.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] In territories with a Westminster system, most bills that have any possibility of becoming law are introduced into parliament by the government.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] This will usually happen following the publication of a "white paper", setting out the issues and the way in which the proposed new law is intended to deal with them.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] A bill may also be introduced into parliament without formal government backing; this is known as a private member's bill.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] In territories with a multicameral parliament, most bills may be first introduced in any chamber.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] However, certain types of legislation are required, either by constitutional convention or by law, to be introduced into a specific chamber.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] For example, bills imposing a tax, or involving public expenditure, are introduced into the House of Commons in the United Kingdom, Canada's House of Commons, Lok Sabha of India and Ireland's Dáil as a matter of law.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Conversely, bills proposed by the Law Commission and consolidation bills traditionally start in the House of Lords.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Once introduced, a bill must go through a number of stages before it can become law.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] In theory, this allows the bill's provisions to be debated in detail, and for amendments to the original bill to also be introduced, debated, and agreed to.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] In bicameral parliaments, a bill that has been approved by the chamber into which it was introduced then sends the bill to the other chamber.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Broadly speaking, each chamber must separately agree to the same version of the bill.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Finally, the approved bill receives assent; in most territories this is merely a formality and is often a function exercised by the head of state.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] In some countries, such as in France, Belgium, Luxembourg, Spain and Portugal, the term for a bill differs depending on whether it is initiated by the government (when it is known as a "draft"), or by the parliament (a "proposition", i.e., a private member's bill).
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Second reading: As in the UK, the stage involves a debate on the general principles of the bill and is followed by a vote.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Again, the second reading of a government bill is usually approved.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] A defeat for a government bill on this reading signifies a major loss.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Consideration in detail: This usually takes place on the floor of the House.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Generally, committees sit on the floor of the House and consider the bill in detail.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Third reading: A debate on the final text of the bill, as amended.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Very rarely do debates occur during this stage.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Passage: The bill is then sent to the other House (to the Senate, if it originated in the House of Representatives; to the House of Representatives, if it is a Senate bill), which may amend it.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] If the other House amends the bill, the bill and amendments are posted back to the original House for a further stage.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] The State of Queensland's Parliament is unicameral and skips this and the rest of the stages.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Consideration of Senate/Representatives amendments: The House in which the bill originated considers the amendments made in the other House.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] It may agree to them, amend them, propose other amendments in lieu, or reject them.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] However, the Senate may not amend money bills, though it can "request" the House to make amendments.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] A bill may pass backward and forward several times at this stage, as each House amends or rejects changes proposed by the other.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] If each House insists on disagreeing with the other, the bill is lost.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Disagreement between the Houses: Often, when a bill cannot be passed in the same form by both Houses, it is "laid aside", i.e. abandoned.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] In the federal Parliament, there is also a special constitutional procedure allowing the passage of the bill without the separate agreement of both houses.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] If the House twice passes the same bill, and the Senate twice fails to pass that bill (either through rejection or through the passage of unacceptable amendments), then the Governor-General may dissolve both Houses of Parliament simultaneously and call an election for the entire Parliament.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] After the election, if the House again passes the bill, but the deadlock between the Houses persists, then the Governor-General may convene a joint sitting of both Houses, where a final decision will be taken on the bill.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Although the House and the Senate sit as a single body, bills passed at a joint sitting are treated as if they had been passed by each chamber separately.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] The procedure only applies if the bill originated in the House of Representatives.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Six double dissolutions have occurred, though a joint sitting was only held once, in 1974.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] The bill is sent to the viceroy (the Governor-General for the Commonwealth; the governor for a state; the administrator for a territory) for royal assent.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Acts in the Australian Capital Territory do not require this step.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Second reading: This stage involves a debate on the general principles of the bill and is followed by a vote.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] The second reading of a government bill is usually approved.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] If the bill is read a second time, then it progresses to the committee stage.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Committee stage: This usually takes place in a standing committee of the Commons or Senate.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Report stage: this takes place on the floor of the appropriate chamber, and allows the House or Senate to approve amendments made in committee, or to propose new ones.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Passage: The bill is then sent to the other House (to the Senate, if it originated in the House of Commons; to the Commons, if it is a Senate bill), where it will face a virtually identical process.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] If the other House amends the bill, the bill and amendments are sent back to the original House for a further stage.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Consideration of Senate/Commons amendments: The House in which the bill originated considers the amendments made in the other House.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] It may agree to them, amend them, propose other amendments in lieu or reject them.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Disagreement between the Houses: There is no specific procedure to resolve a dispute between the houses.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Either house can amend or reject a bill.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] The debate on each stage is actually debate on a specific motion.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] For the first reading, there is no debate.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] In the Report stage, the debate is on the motions for specific amendments.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Once a bill has passed both Houses in an identical form, it is presented to the Governor General, who gives it royal assent.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Although the Governor General can refuse to assent a bill, this power has never been exercised.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Bills being reviewed by Parliament are assigned numbers: 2 to 200 for government bills, 201 to 1000 for private member's bills, and 1001 up for private bills.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] They are preceded by C- if they originate in the House of Commons, or S- if they originate in the Senate.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] For example, Bill C-250 was a private member's bill introduced in the House.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Bills C-1 and S-1 are pro forma bills, and are introduced at the beginning of each session in order to assert the right of each Chamber to manage its own affairs.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] They are introduced and read a first time, and then are dropped from the Order Paper.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Second reading – discussion stage: This stage consists of detailed consideration of the bill and proposed amendments.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Third reading – voting stage: This stage is confined only to arguments either in support of the bill or for its rejection as a whole, without referring to its details.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] After the bill is passed, it is sent to the other house.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Bill in the other house (Rajya Sabha): After a bill, other than a money bill, is transmitted to the other house, it goes through all the stages in that house as that in the first house.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] But if the bill passed by one house is amended by the other house, it goes back to the originating house.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] President's approval: When a bill is passed by both the houses, it is sent to the President for his approval.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] The President can assent or withhold his assent to a bill or he can return a bill, other than a money bill.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] If the President gives his assent, the bill is published in *The Gazette of India* and becomes an Act from the date of his assent.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] If he withholds his assent, the bill is dropped, which is known as pocket veto.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] The pocket veto is not written in the constitution and has only been exercised once, by President Zail Singh in 1986, over the postal act where the government wanted to open postal letters without warrant.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] If the president returns it for reconsideration, the Parliament must do so, but if it is passed again and returned to him, he must give his assent to it.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] In the Irish Parliament, the Oireachtas, bills pass through the following stages.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Bills may be initiated in either the Dáil or the Seanad, and must pass both houses.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Second stage – this involves a discussion of the general principle of the bill.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] It is introduced by the sponsoring minister (or in the case of a private member's bill, by the member) and is followed by contributions from the floor of the house.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Finally, the debate is brought to a conclusion by voting on the proposal "that the bill now be read a second time".
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Third stage, commonly referred to as the Committee Stage.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] This involves section by section scrutiny of the bill and any amendments which have been tabled.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] In the Dáil this usually takes place in a committee room and will involve examination by one of the select committees.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] In the Seanad, this stage takes place in the chamber.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] The Seanad may only make recommendations rather than amendments, in the case of a money bill.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Fourth stage, commonly referred to as the Report Stage.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] At this point, a version of the bill incorporating any changes made at the Committee Stage is printed for consideration.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] In both houses, this stage is taken on the floor of the chamber.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Amendments may be considered at this stage but must arise from matters discussed or changes made at the Committee Stage.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Fifth stage: in practice this is a formality, taken with the fourth stage and referred to as the Report and Final Stage.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Passage in the other house: the same stages are repeated in the other house and the bill is then deemed to have been passed, except that any bill initiated in the Dáil and amended by the Seanad must return to the Dáil for final consideration.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Signature: once the bill has passed both houses it is sent to the President for signature.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] The signed copy is then enrolled in the Office of the Supreme Court.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Select committee stage: The bill is considered by a select committee, which scrutinises the bill in detail and hears public submissions on the matter.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] The select committee may recommend amendments to the bill.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Second reading: The general principles of the bill are debated, and a vote is held.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] If the bill is approved, it is put before a Committee of the House.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Committee of the House: The bill is debated and voted on, clause by clause, by the whole House sitting as a committee.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Third reading: Summarising arguments are made, and a final vote is taken.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] If the bill is approved, it is passed to the Governor-General for royal assent.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] New Zealand has no upper house, and so no further approval is necessary.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] A draft piece of legislation is called a *bill*; when this is passed by Parliament it becomes an *act* and part of statute law.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] There are two types of bill and act, *public* and *private*.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Public acts apply to the whole of the UK or a number of its constituent countries – England, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Private acts are local and personal in their effect, giving special powers to bodies such as local authorities or making exceptions to the law in particular geographic areas.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] First reading: This is a formality; no vote occurs.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] The bill is presented and ordered to be printed and, in the case of private members' bills, a date is set for second reading.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Second reading: A debate on the general principles of the bill is followed by a vote.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Committee stage: This usually takes place in a public bill committee in the Commons and on the floor of the House in the Lords.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] The committee considers each clause of the bill, and may make amendments to it.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Consideration (or report) stage: This takes place on the floor of the House, and is a further opportunity to amend the bill.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Unlike committee stage, the House need not consider every clause of the bill, only those to which amendments have been tabled.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Third reading: A debate on the final text of the bill, as amended in the House of Lords.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Further amendments may be tabled at this stage.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Passage: The bill is then sent to the other House (to the Lords, if it originated in the Commons; to the Commons, if it is a Lords bill), which may amend it.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Consideration of Lords/Commons amendments: The House in which the bill originated considers the amendments made in the other House.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Royal assent: the bill is passed with any amendments and becomes an act of Parliament.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Stage one: The bill is considered by one or more of the subject committees of the parliament, which normally take evidence from the bill's promoter and other interested parties before reporting to the parliament on the principles of the bill.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Other committees, notably the Finance and Subordinate Legislation Committees, may also feed in at this stage.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] The report from the committee is followed by a debate in the full parliament.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Stage two: The bill returns to the subject committee where it is subject to line-by-line scrutiny and amendment.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] This is similar to the committee stage in the UK Parliament.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Stage three: The bill as amended by the committee returns to the full parliament.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] There is a further opportunity for amendment, followed by a debate on the whole bill, at the end of which the parliament decides whether to pass the bill.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Royal assent: After the bill has been passed, the presiding officer submits it to the monarch for royal assent.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] However, he cannot do so until a four-week period has elapsed during which the law officers of the Scottish government or the UK government can refer the bill to the Supreme Court of the United Kingdom for a ruling on whether it is within the powers of the parliament.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] There are special procedures for emergency bills, member's bills (similar to private member's bills in the UK Parliament), committee bills, and private bills.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] In Singapore, the bill passes through these certain stages before becoming into an Act of Parliament.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Second reading: In this stage, the bill is further discussed and put to a second vote.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] If more than half of the votes are ayes the bill proceeds to the select committee.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Select committee: The select committee consists of people not only from the parliaments, but also the people who could be affected by the bill is passed into law.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] This is to ensure equality and that the bill is fair for all.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] If the bill is in favour, it will proceed to the third reading.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Third reading: After the select committee has discussed and are in favour of the bill, they will put it to a vote.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] At this juncture, if the votes are more than half ayes, it will be sent to the President of Singapore.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] President Assent: The president must give permission in order for the bill to be passed.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] If they approve it, it will become a statute passed down by the members of parliament which is called an Act of Parliament.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Acts passed by the Parliament of England did not originally have titles, and could only be formally cited by reference to the parliamentary session in which they were passed, with each individual act being identified by year and chapter number.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Descriptive titles began to be added to the enrolled acts by the official clerks, as a reference aid; over time, titles came to be included within the text of each bill.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Since the mid-nineteenth century, it has also become common practice for acts to have a short title, as a convenient alternative to the sometimes lengthy main titles.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] The Short Titles Act 1892, and its replacement the Short Titles Act 1896, gave short titles to many acts which previously lacked them.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] The numerical citation of acts has also changed over time.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] The original method was based on the regnal year (or years) in which the relevant parliamentary session met.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] This has been replaced in most territories by simple reference to the calendar year, with the first act passed being chapter 1, and so on.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] In the United Kingdom, legislation has referenced by year and chapter number since 1963 (Acts of Parliament Numbering and Citation Act 1962).
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Each act is numbered consecutively based on the date it received royal assent, for example the 43rd act passed in 1980 would be 1980 chapter 43.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] The full reference includes the (short) title and would be the Magistrate's Court Act 1980 (c.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-parliament] Until the 1980s, acts of the Australian state of Victoria were numbered in a continuous sequence from 1857; thus the Age of Majority Act 1977 was No.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] The **Acts of Union** refer to two acts of Parliament, one by the Parliament of Scotland in March 1707, followed shortly thereafter by an equivalent act of the Parliament of England.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] They put into effect the international Treaty of Union agreed on 22 July 1706, which politically joined the Kingdom of England and Kingdom of Scotland into a single "political state" named Great Britain, with Queen Anne as its sovereign.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] The English and Scottish acts of ratification took effect on 1 May 1707, creating the new kingdom, with its parliament based in the Palace of Westminster.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] The two countries had shared a monarch since the "personal" Union of the Crowns in 1603, when James VI of Scotland inherited the English throne from his cousin Elizabeth I to become (in addition) 'James I of England', styled James VI and I.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Prior to 1603, England and Scotland had different monarchs, but when Elizabeth I died without children, she was succeeded as King of England by her distant relative, James VI of Scotland.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] After her death, the two Crowns were held in personal union by James (reigning as James VI and I), who announced his intention to unite the two realms.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] The 1603 Union of England and Scotland Act established a joint Commission to agree terms, but the Parliament of England was concerned this would lead to an absolutist structure similar to that of Scotland.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] James was forced to withdraw his proposals, but used the royal prerogative to take the title "King of Great Britain".
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Attempts to revive the project of union in 1610 were met with hostility.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] English opponents such as Sir Edwin Sandys argued that changing the name of England "were as yf [*sic*] to make a conquest of our name, which was more than ever the Dane or Norman could do".
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Instead, James set about creating a unified Church of Scotland and England, as the first step towards a centralised, Unionist state.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] However, despite both being nominally Episcopal in structure, the two were very different in doctrine; the Church of Scotland, or kirk, was Calvinist in doctrine, and viewed many Church of England practices as little better than Catholicism.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] As a result, attempts to impose religious policy by James and his son Charles I ultimately led to the 1639–1651 Wars of the Three Kingdoms.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] The 1639–1640 Bishops' Wars confirmed the primacy of the Scots kirk, and established a Covenanter government in Scotland.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] The Scots remained neutral when the First English Civil War began in 1642, before becoming concerned at the impact on Scotland of an English Royalist victory.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Presbyterian leaders like Argyll viewed union as a way to ensure free trade between England and Scotland, and preserve a Scots Presbyterian kirk.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Under the 1643 Solemn League and Covenant, the Scots Parliament agreed to provide military support to its English counterpart in return for a united Presbyterian church, but did not explicitly commit to political union.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] As the war progressed, Scots and English Presbyterians increasingly viewed the English Independents, and associated radical groups like the Levellers, as a bigger threat than the Royalists.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Both Royalists and Presbyterians agreed monarchy was divinely ordered, but disagreed on the nature and extent of Royal authority over the church.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] When Charles I surrendered in 1646, an English pro-Royalist faction known as the Engagers allied with their former enemies to restore him to the English throne.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] After defeat in the 1647–1648 Second English Civil War, Scotland was occupied by English troops, which were withdrawn once those whom Cromwell held responsible had been replaced by the Kirk Party.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] In December 1648, Pride's Purge paved the way for the Trial of Charles I in England by excluding MPs who opposed it.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Following the execution of Charles I in January 1649, and establishment of the Commonwealth of England, the Scots Kirk Party proclaimed Charles II King of Scots and England and, in the 1650 Treaty of Breda, resolved to restore him to the English throne.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Instead, defeat in the Anglo-Scottish War resulted in Scotland's incorporation into the Commonwealth in 1653, largely driven by Cromwell's determination to break the power of the Scots kirk.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] The 1652 Tender of Union was followed on 12 April 1654 by *An Ordinance by the Protector for the Union of England and Scotland,* creating the Commonwealth of England and Scotland.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] It was ratified by the Second Protectorate Parliament on 26 June 1657, creating a single Parliament in Westminster, with 30 representatives each from Scotland and Ireland added to the existing English members.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] While integration into the Commonwealth established free trade between Scotland and England, the economic benefits were diminished by the costs of military occupation.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Both Scotland and England associated union with heavy taxes and military rule; it had little popular support in either Country, and the union was dissolved after the Restoration of Charles II in 1660.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was badly damaged by the (protectionist) English Navigation Acts of 1660 and 1663 and England's wars with the Dutch Republic, Scotland's major export market.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] An Anglo-Scots Trade Commission was set up in January 1668 but the English had no interest in making concessions, as the Scots had little to offer in return.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] In 1669, Charles II revived talks on "political union"; his motives may have been to weaken Scotland's commercial and political links with the Dutch, still seen as an enemy and complete the work of his grandfather James I and VI.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] On the Scottish side, the proposed union received parliamentary support, boosted by the desire to ensure free trade.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Continued opposition meant these negotiations were abandoned by the end of 1669.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] The Convention of the Estates issued an address to William and Mary "as both kingdomes are united in one head and soveraigne so they may become one body pollitick, one nation to be represented in one parliament", reserving "our church government, as it shall be established at the tyme of the union".
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] William and Mary were supportive of the idea but it was opposed both by the Presbyterian majority in Scotland and the English Parliament.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Episcopacy in Scotland was abolished in 1690, alienating a significant part of the political class; it was this element that later formed the bedrock of opposition to Union.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] The 1690s were a time of economic hardship in Europe as a whole and Scotland in particular, a period now known as the Seven ill years which led to strained relations with England.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] In 1698, the Company of Scotland Trading to Africa and the Indies received a charter to raise capital through public subscription.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] The Company invested in the Darién scheme, an ambitious plan funded almost entirely by Scottish investors to build a colony on the Isthmus of Panama for trade with East Asia.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] The scheme was a disaster; the losses of over £150,000 severely impacted the Scottish commercial system.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] The International Treaty, and English and Scots acts of ratification of Union may be seen within a wider European context of increasing state centralisation during the late 17th and early 18th centuries, including the monarchies of France, Sweden, Denmark-Norway and Spain.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] While there were exceptions, such as the Dutch Republic or the Republic of Venice, the trend was clear.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] The dangers of the monarch using one parliament against the other first became apparent in 1647 and 1651.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] It resurfaced during the 1679 to 1681 Exclusion Crisis, caused by English resistance to the Catholic prince James (later James II of England, James VII of Scots) succeeding his brother Charles II.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] It then went beyond ensuring James's succession to the Scots throne by explicitly stating the aim was to make his exclusion from the English throne impossible without "the fatall and dreadfull consequences of a civil war".
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] The issue reappeared during the 1688 Dutch invasion and *coup d'etat* (subsequently entitled as "the Glorious Revolution").
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] The English Convention Parliament generally supported replacing James with his Protestant daughter Mary, holding to their "legal fiction" that James, by fleeing to France, had abandoned his English subjects and "abdicated".
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] They initially resisted making her Dutch husband William of Orange joint ruler but relented, "fearing the return of James" only when William threatened to take his troops and fleet and return to the Netherlands, and Mary refused to rule without him.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] In Scotland, it became a Constitutional issue.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] The fact that King James had not been present in Scotland meant that the question of abdication need not arise.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] On 4 April 1689 a Convention of the Three Estates of Scotland (sister body to the Parliament of Scotland) declared that James "had acted irregularly" by assuming regal power (government) "without ever taking the Coronation Oath required by Scots Law".
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Thus, he had "FOREFALTED [forfeited] the Right to the Scots Crown, and the Scots Throne is become vacant".
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] "Scots monarchs derived legitimacy from the Convention of the Estates", later declared a Parliament of Scotland, not God, thus ending the principle of divine right of kings.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Conflict over control of the kirk between Presbyterians and Episcopalians and William's position as a fellow Calvinist put him in a much stronger position.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] He originally insisted on retaining Episcopacy, and the Committee of the Articles, an unelected body that controlled what legislation Parliament could debate.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Both would have given the Crown far greater control than in England but he withdrew his demands due to the 1689–1692 Jacobite Rising.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] 2. the Convention of the Estates was a parliament and so parliament could just rewrite it.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Here is the Claim of Right understood and upheld for its secular constitutional provisions quite as much as for its religious provisions.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] The English succession was provided for by the English Act of Settlement 1701, which ensured that the monarch of England would be a Protestant member of the House of Hanover.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Until the union of parliaments, the Scottish throne might be inherited by a different successor after Queen Anne, who had said in her first speech to the English parliament that a union was "very necessary".
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] The Scottish Act of Security 1704, however, was passed after the English parliament, without consultation with Scotland, had designated Electoress Sophia of Hanover (granddaughter of James I and VI) as Anne's successor, if Anne died childless.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] The Act of Security granted the Parliament of Scotland, the three Estates, the right to choose a successor and explicitly required a choice different from the English monarch unless the English were to grant free trade and navigation.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Then the Alien Act 1705 was passed in the English parliament, designating Scots in England as "foreign nationals" and blocking about half of all Scottish trade by boycotting exports to England or its colonies, unless Scotland came back to negotiate a Union.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] To encourage a union, "honours, appointments, pensions and even arrears of pay and other expenses were distributed to clinch support from Scottish peers and MPs".
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was severely impacted by privateers during the 1688–1697 Nine Years' War and the 1701 War of the Spanish Succession, with the Royal Navy focusing on protecting English ships.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] This compounded the economic pressure caused by the Darien scheme, and the seven ill years of the 1690s, when 5–15% of the population died of starvation.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament was promised financial assistance, protection for its maritime trade, and an end to economic restrictions on trade with England.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] The votes of the Court party, influenced by Queen Anne's favourite, James Douglas, 2nd Duke of Queensberry, combined with the majority of the Squadrone Volante, were sufficient to ensure passage of the treaty.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] The role played by bribery has long been debated. £20,000 was distributed by David Boyle, 1st Earl of Glasgow, of which 60% went to the Duke of Queensberry, the Queen's Commissioner in Parliament.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Another negotiator, John Campbell, 2nd Duke of Argyll was given an English dukedom.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Professor Sir Tom Devine agreed that promises of "favours, sinecures, pensions, offices and straightforward cash bribes became indispensable to secure government majorities".
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] As for representation going forwards, Scotland was, in the new united parliament, only to get 45 MPs, one more than Cornwall, and only 16 (unelected) peers in the House of Lords.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] There were mixed opinions in Scotland about the prospect of a union with England.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Sir George Lockhart of Carnwath, the only Scottish negotiator to oppose Union, noted "the whole nation appears against (it)".
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Another negotiator, Sir John Clerk of Penicuik, who was an ardent Unionist, observed it was "contrary to the inclinations of at least three-fourths of the Kingdom".
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] As the seat of the Scottish Parliament, demonstrators in Edinburgh feared the impact of its loss on the local economy.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Elsewhere, there was widespread concern about the independence of the kirk, and possible tax rises.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Virtually all of the print discourses of 1699–1706 spoke against incorporating union, creating the conditions for widespread rejection of the treaty in 1706 and 1707.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] In the wake of unionist proselytising in the autumn of 1706 and early 1707, many Scots were undecided about the prospect of a union.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Rather, there was considerably more support in Scotland for a federal union with England than an incorporative one, similar to the devolved Scottish parliament that would be established within Britain nearly three centuries later.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] As the treaty passed through the Parliament of Scotland, opposition was voiced by petitions from shires, burghs, presbyteries and parishes.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] According to Christopher Whatley, however, calls for a union with England began in Scotland itself in the 1690s for the purpose of safeguarding the law, line of succession, and to improve the economy.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Ireland, though a kingdom under the same crown, was not included in the union.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] It remained a separate kingdom, unrepresented in Parliament, and was legally subordinate to Great Britain until the Renunciation Act 1783.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] In July 1707 each House of the Parliament of Ireland passed a congratulatory address to Queen Anne, praying that "May God put it in your royal heart to add greater strength and lustre to your crown, by a still more comprehensive Union".
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] The British government did not respond to the invitation and an equal union between Great Britain and Ireland was out of consideration until the 1790s.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] The union with Ireland finally came about on 1 January 1801.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Deeper political integration had been a key policy of Queen Anne from the time she acceded to the throne in 1702.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Under the aegis of the Queen and her ministers in both kingdoms, the parliaments of England and Scotland (the **Act for a Treaty with England 1705**) agreed to participate in fresh negotiations for a union treaty in 1705.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Both countries appointed 31 commissioners to conduct the negotiations.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Most of the Scottish commissioners favoured union, and about half were government ministers and other officials.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] At the head of the list was the Duke of Queensberry, and the Lord Chancellor of Scotland, the Earl of Seafield.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] The English commissioners included the Lord High Treasurer, Sidney Godolphin, 1st Earl of Godolphin, the Lord Keeper of the Great Seal, William Cowper, Baron Cowper, and a large number of Whigs who supported union.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Tories were not in favour of union and only one was represented among the commissioners.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Negotiations between the English and Scottish commissioners took place between 16 April and 22 July 1706 at the Cockpit in London.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Each side had its own particular concerns.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] After negotiations ended in July 1706, the acts had to be ratified by both Parliaments.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] In Scotland, about 100 of the 227 members of the Parliament of Scotland were supportive of the Court Party.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] For extra votes the pro-court side could rely on about 25 members of the Squadrone Volante, led by the James Graham, 4th Marquess of Montrose and John Ker, 1st Duke of Roxburghe.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] The Court party enjoyed significant funding from England and the Treasury and included many who had accumulated debts following the Darien Disaster.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] The act ratifying the Treaty of Union was finally carried in the Parliament of Scotland by 110 votes to 69 on 16 January 1707, with a number of key amendments.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] News of the ratification and of the amendments was received in Westminster, where the Act was passed quickly through both Houses and received the royal assent on 6 March.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Though the English Act was later in date, it bore the year '1706' while Scotland's was '1707', as the legal year in England began only on 25 March.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] In Scotland, the Duke of Queensberry was largely responsible for the successful passage of the Union act by the Parliament of Scotland.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] In Scotland, he was greeted by stones and eggs but in England he was cheered for his action.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] He had personally received around half of the funding awarded by the Westminster Treasury.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] In April 1707, he travelled to London to attend celebrations at the royal court, and was greeted by groups of noblemen and gentry lined along the road.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] From Barnet, the route was lined with crowds of cheering people, and once he reached London a huge crowd had formed.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] On 17 April, the Duke was gratefully received by the Queen at Kensington Palace and the Acts came into effect on 1 May 1707.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] A day of thanksgiving was declared in England and Ireland but not in Scotland, where the bells of St Giles rang out the tune of *"why should I be so sad on my wedding day"*.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] The Treaty of Union, agreed between representatives of the Parliament of England and the Parliament of Scotland in 1706, consisted of 25 articles, 15 of which were economic in nature.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] In Scotland, each article was voted on separately and several clauses in articles were delegated to specialised subcommittees.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Article 1 of the treaty was based on the political principle of an incorporating union and this was secured by a majority of 116 votes to 83 on 4 November 1706.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] To minimise the opposition of the Church of Scotland, an Act was also passed to secure the Presbyterian establishment of the Church, after which the Church stopped its open opposition, although hostility remained at lower levels of the clergy.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] The treaty as a whole was finally ratified on 16 January 1707 by a majority of 110 votes to 69.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] The two Acts incorporated provisions for Scotland to send representative peers from the Peerage of Scotland to sit in the House of Lords.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] It guaranteed that the Church of Scotland would remain the established church in Scotland, that the Court of Session would "remain in all time coming within Scotland", and that Scots law would "remain in the same force as before".
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Other provisions included the restatement of the Act of Settlement 1701 and the ban on Roman Catholics from taking the throne.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] It also created a customs union and monetary union.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] The Act provided that any "laws and statutes" that were "contrary to or inconsistent with the terms" of the Act would "cease and become void".
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament also passed the Protestant Religion and Presbyterian Church Act 1707 guaranteeing the status of the Presbyterian Church of Scotland.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] The English Parliament passed a similar Act, 6 Ann. c.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] 40—later named the Union with Scotland (Amendment) Act 1707—united the Privy Council of England and Privy Council of Scotland and decentralised Scottish administration by appointing justices of the peace in each shire to carry out administration.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] In effect it took the day-to-day government of Scotland out of the hands of politicians and into those of the College of Justice.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] On 18 December 1707 the Act for better Securing the Duties of East India Goods was passed which extended the monopoly of the East India Company to Scotland.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] In the year following the Union, the Treason Act 1708 abolished the Scottish law of treason and extended the corresponding English law across Great Britain.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Clark, gaining "freedom of trade with England and the colonies" as well as "a great expansion of markets".
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] The agreement guaranteed the permanent status of the Presbyterian church in Scotland, and the separate system of laws and courts in Scotland.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] However, the Scottish economy was lagging behind not only from the impact of wars, but also because of chronic deflation and industrial underdevelopment.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Scotland remained a predominantly agrarian society, and the lack of manpower caused by previous conflicts contributed to an underwhelming agricultural output, which intermittently escalated into local food shortages or famines.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] In turn, the overreliance of Scottish landowners on foreign goods led to a deficit of financial capital, as gold and silver were exported overseas and deflation occurred.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament attempted to combat the issue by attracting foreign investment; duty on ship building materials was lifted, taxes on new manufacturing stocks were cut, and customs on textile and linen goods were removed.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Scotland grew increasingly dependent on its linen industry, which became the biggest source of employment after agriculture and constituted one-third of Scottish industry.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Continental linen industries could outcompete Scotland, and protectionist tariffs implemented by Scotland led to tariff wars as European countries closed their markets to Scotland.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] In this situation, England became the largest foreign market for Scottish linen; however, while the tariffs in place shielded Scotland from the much larger English industry, England also retaliated against them.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] This forced Scotland to seek economic alternatives.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] At the time, trade with colonies was rapidly growing in importance in Europe, and trade with colonies was very attractive to Scotland, given its pastoral economy.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] American colonies had a high demand of agricultural goods such as leather skins of goats and sheep, which would have provided Scotland a valuable source of income.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Search for colonial trade, along with the frustration caused by economic and political rivalry with England, led to the Darien scheme – an unsuccessful attempt to establish a Scottish colony in the Gulf of Darién.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] The failure of the Darien scheme led to a financial crisis in Scotland.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] The high cost of its project exacerbated the deflation in Scotland.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] The Bank of Scotland had dangerously low reserves, and in early 1700s a run on the bank occurred, along with temporary suspension of business.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Ultimately, the Scottish bank managed to stay solvent, although the persisting deflation and low reserves largely contributed to the feeling of Scottish economy being in a precarious position.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Economist Aida Ramos argues that the Darien scheme could have succeeded if it was to receive support from either England or Spain, and that it lacked the capability to create a threat to England or its interests.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] According to Ramos, the English intervention against the scheme was to meet the expansionary aims of England, as to ensure both its colonial dominance as well as the annexation of Scotland.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] By 1703, the Scottish government was highly disillusioned with the union, and many believed that the only way to let the Scottish economy flourish was to separate from England.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Scotland would try to establish further autonomy from England with the Act of Security 1704, which provoked a retaliation from England – Scottish ministers were bribed, and Alien Act 1705 was passed.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] According to the Alien Act, unless Scotland appointed commissioners to negotiate for union by Christmas, every Scot in England would be treated as an alien, leading to the confiscation of their English estates.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Additionally, Scottish wares were to be banned from England.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was now facing a crisis, and the parliament was polarised into pro-union and anti-union factions, with the former led by Daniel Defoe.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] The unionists stressed how important trade with England is to the Scottish economy, and seen trade with continental Europe as not beneficial.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] They argued that the Scottish economy could survive by trading with England, and sanctions that would result from the Alien Act would collapse the economy.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] For Defoe, joining the union would not only prevent the Alien Act, but also remove additional limitations and regulations and lead Scotland to prosperity.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Anti-unionists questioned the English goodwill and criticised the unionist faction for submitting to the English blackmail.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] They argued that Scotland could make a recovery by trading with the Netherlands, Spain and Norway, allowing Scotland to diversify its own industries as well.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] They argued that the union would make Scotland unable to conduct independent trade policy, meaning that any possibility to remove the flaws in Scottish economy would be gone forever, which would turn Scotland into a "mere satellite of the richer kingdom".
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Ultimately, Scottish ministers voted in favour of the union, despite the lack of public support, with the overwhelming majority of the Scottish population at the time protesting vociferously against any union with England.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Many Scots considered themselves to have been betrayed by their own elites, and that the union bill was able to pass only thanks to English bribery.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] In the first few decades after the union, England did not end up becoming the main trading partner of Scotland, as other European powers became the primary source of imported goods for Scotland.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] For at least the first 40 years after the union, Scotland persisted in its traditional trade patterns, and the economic situation of Scotland was not as dire as that described in the months leading up to the Acts of Union.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] Christopher Whatley writes, however, that by 1799, it was reported that the union of Scotland with England had not only benefitted the Scottish economy, but promoted a "commercial prosperity" unknown to any people.
[src:disruption-of-1843/act-of-union-1707] A commemorative two-pound coin was issued to mark the tercentennial—300th anniversary—of the Union, which occurred two days before the Scottish Parliament general election on 3 May 2007.
[src:disruption-of-1843/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] ACTS was the successor to the former Scottish Council of Churches.
[src:disruption-of-1843/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] It was one of the four national ecumenical bodies in the UK, with equivalent bodies being Churches Together in England, Cytûn in Wales and the Irish Council of Churches, plus Churches Together in Britain and Ireland.
[src:disruption-of-1843/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] The ACTS office was originally located in Dunblane, then in Alloa and finally in Stirling.
[src:disruption-of-1843/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] In 2019, the General Assembly of the Church of Scotland announced that ACTS would be succeeded by a new body to be called the Scottish Christian Forum.
[src:disruption-of-1843/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] In 2021 it was decided not to establish the SCF as a charity.
[src:disruption-of-1843/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] In 2024 the Scottish Christian Forum was recognised by Scottish churches as the main ecumenical organisation for Scotland.
[src:disruption-of-1843/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] It is an umbrella term for the Ecumenical Officers Forum and the Scottish Church Leaders' Forum.
[src:disruption-of-1843/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] ACTS continues in existence as a charity, its principle activity being to provide grant aid to new local or national ecumenical initiatives in Scotland.
[src:disruption-of-1843/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] From May 2018, the interim general secretary was the Rev.
[src:disruption-of-1843/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] Ian Boa (who succeeded the Reverend Matthew Ross, a minister of the Church of Scotland, who took up a new post with the World Council of Churches).
[src:disruption-of-1843/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] The assistant general secretary (since 2011) was the Reverend Ian Boa of the United Free Church of Scotland; he succeeded the Revd Lindsey Sanderson of the United Reformed Church.
[src:disruption-of-1843/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] There were also two programme officers to support the work of ACTS.
[src:disruption-of-1843/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] When first created, the office of ACTS was located at the former *Scottish Churches House* in Dunblane.
[src:disruption-of-1843/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] In 2006 the ACTS office was moved to Forrester Lodge, adjacent to Inglewood House in Alloa, but in October 2015 it was relocated to Stirling, in a self-contained office within the headquarters building of *Volunteer Scotland*.
[src:disruption-of-1843/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] Scottish Churches House was opened in 1960, closed in 2011 and subsequently converted into a hotel.
[src:disruption-of-1843/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] ACTS was a place for churches to meet, experience, reflect, share and act together.
[src:disruption-of-1843/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] There were a number of projects which ACTS coordinates across Scotland.
[src:disruption-of-1843/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] It was not intended that ACTS should develop into a "superchurch".
[src:disruption-of-1843/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] Prior to 2003, four member churches of ACTS were part of the "Scottish Churches Initiative for Union" (which sought institutional unity - a project which ACTS was not part of), but a negative vote at the General Assembly in 2003 necessitated the withdrawal of the Church of Scotland from SCIFU.
[src:disruption-of-1843/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] Henceforth, greater emphasis has been placed on the development of Local Ecumenical Partnerships.
[src:disruption-of-1843/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] The principle of being Churches Together was of central importance to the work of ACTS.
[src:disruption-of-1843/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] The agenda of ACTS was set at a national level by the church denominations through their representatives on the "Members' Meeting".
[src:disruption-of-1843/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] To comply with the requirements of the Office of the Scottish Charity Regulator, the legal responsibility for the oversight and governance of ACTS is vested in trustees, chaired by the convener of ACTS and supported by the Secretariat.
[src:disruption-of-1843/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] As of 2025 the board of trustees remains in existence.
[src:disruption-of-1843/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] ACTS worked through its Programme Groups, Partner Group and Bodies in Association.
[src:disruption-of-1843/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] Programme Groups (directly under the responsibility of ACTS) include the Scottish Churches Rural Group, Scottish Churches Anti-Human Trafficking Group and the Scottish Churches Education Group.
[src:disruption-of-1843/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] Partner Groups (administratively and financially supported by ACTS, but with autonomous management) include the Scottish Churches Racial Justice Group.
[src:disruption-of-1843/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] The ACTS Ecumenical Development Group promoted local ecumenism.
[src:disruption-of-1843/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] Before restructuring in the early 2010s, ACTS had four "Networks".
[src:disruption-of-1843/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] A separate body, the Scottish Churches' Committee, is responsible for liaison with public authorities on legal (rather than spiritual) matters - such as changes to legislation and the resulting effect on churches (such as planning law, changes to local government taxation, etc.).
[src:disruption-of-1843/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] Seven of the nine members of ACTS are also members of the SCC (i.e. all but the two smallest, namely the Congregational Federation and the Quakers).
[src:disruption-of-1843/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] The SCC also includes the Baptist Church, the Free Church of Scotland and several smaller Presbyterian churches.
[src:disruption-of-1843/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] The Secretary of the SCC is the Solicitor of the Church of Scotland.
[src:disruption-of-1843/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] It also co-operates with the UK-wide Churches Legislation Advisory Services (CLAS), formerly known as the Churches' Main Committee.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] In 1833 he was busiest with the Chapel Act, and was actively engaged in promoting anti-patronage meetings; in 1834 he became editor of the "Presbyterian Review.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] In 1835 Church extension occupied him; in 1837 and 1838 the Auchterarder case, the conflict between the Church and the Court of Session, and non-intrusion meetings, absorbed his attention.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] The sympathies of Dunlop were very warmly enlisted in the operations of the church, and he took an active part in all the ecclesiastical reforms and benevolent undertakings of the period.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] But in a pre-eminent degree his interest was excited by the questions relating to the law of patronage, and the collision which arose out of them between the church and the civil courts.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] He not only defended the church at the bar of the court of session, but in private councils, in committees, deputations, and publications he was unwearied on her behalf.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] The public documents in which his position was stated and defended, especially the Claim of Right in 1842, the Protest and Deed of Demission in 1843, were mainly his work.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] Dunlop became an elder in the Church of Scotland in Greenock in 1822.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] On going to Edinburgh he became a member of the kirk-session in St Bernard's church.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] This made it possible for him to take part in the General Assemblies and other church courts.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] From 1845 he was an elder at Free St Georges, Edinburgh.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] Among Church reforms Mr Dunlop took special interest in the restoration of the eldership to its old place in the Church of Scotland.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] He wrote two articles upon this subject in the "Presbyterian Review," and prepared an elaborate report for the General Assembly.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] He also left some historical notes upon the place of the eldership in the ancient Church of Scotland, which were not published in his lifetime.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] Church extension, too, interested him greatly; but, as was natural from his previous studies, the relation of the Church to education and to the poor occupied most of his attention.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] The inforrnation furnished by the Church to the Government about the number of paupers in Scotland, and the elaborate Report on the same subject presented to the Assembly of 1841, were both the result of Mr Dunlop's almost unaided labour.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] He took an active part in the Voluntary controversy.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] His argument, the same in speech and pamphlet, and at last set forth in detail in the Claim of Rights, was substantially this: There is no need in Scotland to dispute about the precise meaning and effects of the abstract doctrine of spiritual independence.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] In virtue of a concordat between Church and State, the Church of Scotland has had certain rights and liberties which can be enumerated, guaranteed her, and recognised as hers.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] These she claims to possess, not merely by inherent right, but also by legal recognition, and these are now being illegally wrested from her.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] On 7 March 1843 the Claim of Rights was finally brought before the House of Commons by Foxe Maule in the British Parliament.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] Maule's motion for a Committee of Inquiry was lost upon a division, by 211 votes to 76.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] Of 36 Scottish members present, 25 voted with Maule.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] Following this the General Assembly met on 18 May 1843, within a large hall at Canonmills, Edinburgh.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] The Moderator, David Welsh, prayed, made some comments and then read a Protest which was again largely written by Dunlop.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] As soon as it was read Welsh handed the paper to the clerk, quitted the chair, and walked away.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] In all 193 members moved off, of whom about 123 were ministers and about 70 elders.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] All, including Dunlop, withdrew slowly and regularly amidst perfect silence till that side of the house was left nearly empty.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] They were joined outside by a large body of adherents, among whom were about 300 clergymen.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] They walked through the streets to Tanfield Hall where a Free Church Assembly had been organised.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] Following this Free Church Assembly another two legal documents the Act of Separation and Deed of Demission, were signed and registered in the books of Council and Session, on 8 June 1843.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] In 1844, he married Eliza Esther, only child of John Murray of Ainslie Place, Edinburgh, and on the death of his father-in-law in 1849, he assumed the name of Murray-Dunlop.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] Subsequently, in 1866, on succeeding to the estate of his cousin, William Colquhoun-Stirling of Law and Edinbarnet, he took the name of Colquhoun-Stirling-Murray-Dunlop.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] He received an honorary LLD from Princeton University.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] In 1845 and 1847, he contested the representation of his native town of Greenock, but without success; in 1852, he was returned by the electors, and for fifteen years represented them.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] In early life he had been a tory, but he was now thoroughly liberal.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] In parliament, however, while generally supporting the liberals he retained an independent position, declining offices both in connection with the government and with his own profession in Scotland, to which his services and abilities well entitled him.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] His services in parliament were fruitful of much useful legislation.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] In a sketch of his life by his friend, David Maclagan, mention is made of eight various acts which he got passed.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] Those on legal points introduced important practical amendments of the laws, the most interesting, perhaps, being that which put a stop to Gretna Green marriages.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] Some of his measures bore on social improvement, one of them being an act to facilitate the erection of dwelling-houses for the working classes, and another an act to render reformatories and industrial schools more available for vagrant and destitute children, well known as Dunlop's Act.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] Another allowed orphans to inherit from their parents rather than the estate being divided by next of kin.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] In the "Arrow" affair, he testified his abhorrence of the conduct of the Liberal Government in the war with China in 1857.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] The defeat of the Ministry involved a general election, and it was felt that many of the Liberals who had voted against the Government would lose their seats.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] Mr Dunlop at once placed his resignation in the hands of his constituency, and declared, with his usual high sense of honour, that he would not even stand as a candidate if they disapproved of his conduct.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] The most chivalrous of his parliamentary services was an attack (19 March 1861) on the government of Henry John Temple, 3rd Viscount Palmerston, which he had usually supported, in connection with the Afghan war.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] Many years after the event, it was ascertained that certain despatches written in 1839 by Sir Alexander Burnes, our envoy at the Afghan court, had been tampered with in publication, and made to express opinions opposite to those which Sir Alexander held.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] Dunlop, at a great sacrifice of feeling, moved on 19 March 1861 for a committee of inquiry, and was very ably supported by Mr.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] Lord Palmerston was put to great straits in his defence, as it could not be denied that Burnes's despatches had been changed; but Benjamin Disraeli came to his rescue, and on the ground that the matter was now twenty years old advised the house not to reopen it.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] On a division, the motion of Dunlop was negatived by a vote of 159 to 49.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] In 1868, he resigned his seat in parliament, the rest of his days being spent chiefly on his property of Corsock in Dumfriesshire.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] Dunlop died on 1 September 1870, in age seventy-one.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] In 1844, Dunlop married Eliza Esther Murray, only child of John Murray of Edinburgh.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] She died at Corsock on 14 July 1902, 84 years old.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-colquhoun-stirling-murray-dunlop] Their eldest daughter was Anna Lindsay whose name was said to be synonymous with women's rights in Scotland.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] Alexander Henderson was born in 1583, and studied at the University of St.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] He was, through the influence of Archbishop Gladstanes, presented to the church living of Leuchars, Fifeshire, and was in 1615 inducted forcibly into the charge.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] He was then a supporter of episcopacy; he subsequently changed his views and became a zealous upholder of Presbyterianism.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] He opposed the adoption of the Five Articles of Perth in 1618, and resisted the use of the Scottish Prayer Book in 1637.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] He drafted both the National Covenant of 1638 with Archibald Johnston, Lord Warriston, and the Solemn League and Covenant of 1643.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] He preached in the Greyfriars church on 28 February 1638, when the National Covenant was signed, and presided as Moderator of the memorable General Assembly held at Glasgow in the following November.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] On two subsequent occasions he was chosen Moderator of Assembly.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] He was Rector of Edinburgh University, and instituted a Professorship of Oriental Languages in that seat of learning.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] With a view to conciliate the Presbyterians, Charles I appointed him his chaplain on his visit to Scotland in 1641.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] At the Restoration the inscriptions on his tombstone were obliterated; they were restored at the Glorious Revolution.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] Alexander Henderson was born at Guthrie, in the Fife parish of Creich, in 1583.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] Of his parentage and family history hardly anything is known.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] Tradition, following from Wodrow, says he was the son of a feuar, and a cadet of the Hendersons of Fordel.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] In support of the latter statement, his remains lie in the burying-ground of that family in Greyfriars Churchyard, and a contemporary portrait of him is still in possession of a representative of that house.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] His birthplace was between the villages of Luthrie and Branton.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] To the maintenance of a school at Luthrie he left two thousand marks Scots in his will.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] On 19 December 1599, at the age of sixteen, he matriculated at St Salvator's College, St Andrews, and took his degree of M.A. in 1603.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] From 1603 to 1611 he was a Regent of Philosophy, and during that period he completed his course in divinity.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] He adopted strong prelatic principles, and was a staunch upholder of Archbishop Gledstanes, who afterwards became his patron, and presented him to the parish of Leuchars.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] His settlement was so unpopular that on the day of his ordination, probably in January 1614, the church doors were found securely nailed up, and he and his friends were obliged to enter by the window.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] Henderson at first showed but little concern for the spiritual interests of his people; but his sentiments and character soon underwent a complete change.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] A Communion sermon preached in a neighbouring parish by Robert Bruce of Kinnaird, was the means of changing Henderson's spiritual outlook.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] Attracted by the fame of the preacher, he slipped (so goes the story) into the darkest corner of the church, hoping to steal out again unrecognised.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] Bruce chose for his text the words: "He that entereth not by the door," etc.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] This passage, so applicable to his situation, and the sermon which followed, made such an impression on his mind as led to an entire change in his views and conduct.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] Bruce, nevertheless, seems to have been aware of his presence; or, if not, there was a singular coincidence in the applicability of the text which he chose, to the remarkable circumstances which attended Henderson's induction to his charge.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] He now became thoroughly convinced that the proceedings of the prelatical party were injurious to the interests of religion, and he resolved at once to take part with the Presbyterians.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] His first appearance in that connection was at the Perth Assembly of 1618, when he strenuously opposed the Five Articles, notwithstanding the threats of the Government.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] Henderson stood among the foremost of those who opposed, though unsuccessfully, the obnoxious measure; and this too, in defiance of the king's utmost wrath, with which all who resisted the adoption of the Five articles were threatened.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] In August 1619 he appeared before the Court of High Commission charged with the publication of a pamphlet denouncing the Perth Assembly.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] Henderson answered the accusation with so much eloquence and truth, that the bishops could gain no advantage over him and his friends, and were obliged to dismiss them with threatenings, and Henderson returned to his parish.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] Of the next eighteen years we know little or nothing.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] With the memorable year 1637 Henderson reappears on the scene, a keen opponent of the Scottish Prayer Book, also known as "Laud's Liturgy," which King Charles was determined to foist on the Church.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] In common with other ministers, he had been charged to purchase two copies of the liturgy for the use of his parish within fifteen days, under the pain of rebellion.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] He immediately went to Edinburgh, and, 23 August, presented a petition to the privy council, representing that the service book had not received the sanction of the General Assembly, nor was recognised by an act of parliament, and praying a suspension of the charge.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] To this remonstrance the council returned a favourable answer, and the reading of the liturgy was ordered to be suspended until the king's farther pleasure should be known.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] Charles, however, only the more peremptorily insisted that the service book should be received; and from this time forward Mr.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] Henderson took a prominent share in all the proceedings of the nonconformists.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] Instead of dispersing, the leaders of the popular party, after some farther ineffectual petitions to the king, resolved to appeal to the people, and the result was the renewal of the National Covenant of 1580 and 1581, with only some slight changes adapted to the circumstances of the times.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] Henderson, assisted by Lord Warrison, Archibald Johnston, an advocate in whom, we are told, the suppliants chiefly confided, and was sworn and subscribed in the Greyfriars' church of Edinburgh, on 28 February 1638, by thousands of the nobility, gentry, ministers of the gospel, burgesses, and others.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] Henderson addressed the vast multitude assembled with great fervour and eloquence, aud the enthusiasm of the people knew no bounds.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] He was subsequently sent with several noblemen, and Messrs.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] Cant and Dickson, to Aberdeen, to prevail on the inhabitants of that city to take the Covenant, and, after urging upon them the strongest arguments in favour of the document, no less than 500 persons subscribed it, many of them being of the highest respectability.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] Mainly through Henderson's influence the National League and Covenant was signed, 21 February 1638, and he was Moderator of the Assembly which met at Glasgow, 21 November of the same year.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] On 1 March 1638 the public signing of the National Covenant began in Greyfriars Kirk, Edinburgh.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] 3. an elaborate oath to maintain the true reformed religion.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] Owing to the skill shown on this occasion he seems to have been applied to when any manifesto of unusual ability was required.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] In July of the same year he proceeded to the north to debate on the Covenant with the famous Aberdeen doctors but he was not well received.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] Robert Baillie wrote: "The Voyd church was made fast, and the keys kept by the magistrate".
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] Henderson's next public opportunity was in the famous Assembly which met in Glasgow on 21 November 1638.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] He was chosen moderator by acclamation, being, as Baillie says, incomparable the ablest man of us all for all things.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] James Hamilton, 1st Duke of Hamilton, was the king's commissioner; and when the Assembly insisted on proceeding with the trial of the bishops, he formally dissolved the meeting under pain of treason.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] During the sitting of this Assembly it was carried by a majority of seventy-five votes that Henderson should be transferred to Edinburgh.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] He had been at Leuchars for about twenty-three years and was extremely reluctant to leave it.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] While Scotland and England were preparing for the First Bishops' War, Henderson drew up two papers, entitled respectively *The Remonstrance of the Nobility* and *Instructions for Defensive Arms*.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] The first of these documents he published himself; the second was published against his wish by John Corbet, a deposed minister.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] The text was written in haste in 1639 and is reported to have been lifted from a work by Johannes Althusius to provide justification for bearing arms.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] The First Bishops' War did not last long.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] At the Pacification of Birks the king virtually granted all the demands of the Scots.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] In the negotiations for peace Henderson was one of the Scottish commissioners, and made a very favourable impression on the king.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] At the memorable General Assembly which met at Glasgow the same year, 21 November 1638, the first that had been held for a long period, Mr.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] Henderson, now the acknowledged leader of the clergy, was unanimously chosen moderator.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] And in that difficult and trying situation, he conducted himself with a resolution and prudence, and at the same time with a forbearance and moderation, befitting the occasion.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] After the deposition and excommunication of the bishops, and the formal abolition of Episcopacy, Mr.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] Before the rising of the Assembly two supplications were given in, the one containing a call to Mr.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] Being much attached to his own parish of Leuchars, of which he had been minister for eighteen years, he expressed his unwillingness to remove from it, pleading that he was now too old a plant to take root in another soil.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] It was carried, however, by seventy-five votes, that he should be translated to Edinburgh; to which he consented, on condition that when old age should overtake him, he should again be removed to a country charge.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] He received calls to St Andrews, and Greyfriars, Edinburgh, and was translated to St.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] Giles, Edinburgh on 10 January 1639, replacing James Hannay.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] He was appointed a Commissioner for framing a treaty of peace with England.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] In 1639 he was one of the commissioners appointed by the Church to treat regarding the articles of pacification with the king; and during the whole of the difficult negotiations that ensued, he behaved with great prudence and candour.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] At the subsequent meeting of the Assembly, in August of that year, John Stewart, 2nd Earl of Traquair, commissioner from his majesty, earnestly desired that Mr.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] Henderson might be re-elected moderator, a proposition strenuously opposed by Mr.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] Henderson himself, and rejected by the Assembly, a constant moderatorship being contrary to the constitution of the Church.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] On the 31st of the same month, he was called upon to preach at the opening of parliament, on which occasion he delivered an excellent discourse, in which he treated, with consummate ability, of the end, duties, and utility of magistrates.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] He declined to be elected Moderator again in 1639.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] The king having refused to ratify some of the points agreed upon at the late pacification, suddenly prorogued the parliament, denounced the Covenanters as rebels, and prepared again to invade Scotland.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] But the successes of the Scots army, which entered England in August 1640, compelled him to accede to another proposition for peace; and a conference was begun at Rippon, which, in a short time after, was transferred to London.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] Before he left London he was admitted to a private conference with the king, the special object of which was to procure assistance to the Scottish universities from the rents formerly appropriated to the bishops, when he was graciously received by his majesty.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] In January 1640 he was Rector of the University of Edinburgh, and held office for the rest of his life.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] In 1640 the town council of Edinburgh, with the view of rendering the system of education at the university more efficient, resolved to appoint annually a rector of that institution, and unanimously elected Mr.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] He was empowered to superintend all matters connected with the conduct of the principal and professors, the education of the students, and the disposal of the revenues.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] In this office, which he appears to have enjoyed, by re-election, to his death, he exerted himself sedulously to promote the interests of that learned seminary.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] Besides devoting his especial attention to the education of candidates for the ministry, he instituted a professorship of oriental languages, a department previously much neglected.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] In 1640 Henderson was elected by the town council rector of Edinburgh University, an office to which he was annually re-elected till his death.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] The Pacification of Birks had been wrung from the king and the Scots, seeing that he was preparing for the Second Bishops' War, took the initiative and pressed into England so vigorously that Charles had again to yield.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] The maturing of the treaty of peace took a considerable time and Henderson was again active in the negotiations, first at Ripon (1 October) and afterwards in London.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] While he was in London he had a personal interview with the king with the view of obtaining assistance for the Scottish universities from money formerly applied to the support of the bishops.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] On Henderson's return to Edinburgh in July 1641, the Assembly was sitting at St Andrews.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] To suit the convenience of the parliament, however, it removed to Edinburgh.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] On his return to Edinburgh, in July 1641, he was again chosen moderator of the General Assembly.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] In this Assembly he proposed that a confession of faith, a catechism, a directory for all the parts of the public worship, and a platform of government wherein possibly England and we might agree, should be drawn up.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] This was unanimously approved and the laborious undertaking was left in Henderson's hands but the notable motion did not lead to any immediate results.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] During Charles's second state visit to Scotland in the autumn of 1641, Henderson acted as his chaplain and managed to get the funds, formerly belonging to the bishopric of Edinburgh, applied to the metropolitan university.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] The Assembly unanimously approved of a motion which he brought forward, to the effect that they should take steps for drawing up a Confession of Faith, Catechism, Directory of Worship, and Form of Government; and remitted to him to prepare the necessary drafts of these documents.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] On 14 August, the king arrived at Edinburgh to be present at the parliament; on which occasion, wishing to conciliate the presbyterian party, he appointed Mr.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] During his majesty's residence in Edinburgh, he performed family worship every morning and evening at the palace, and frequently preached before him in the chapel-royal at Holyroodhouse.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] At this parliament the revenues of the bishoprics were divided; and by Mr.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] Henderson's exertions, what belonged to the bishopric and priory of Edinburgh were bestowed on the university.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] As a recompence for his own laborious and expensive services in the cause of the public, the emoluments of the chapel-royal, amounting to about 4,000 merks a-year, were conferred upon him.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] Some reports injurious to his character having been industriously circulated, in the ensuing Assembly he entered into a long and impassioned vindication of his conduct.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] His brethren unanimously expressed their sympathy, and assured him of their continued confidence; on which we are told he recovered his cheerfulness.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] In 1641, he preached before King Charles at Holyrood, and was made Dean of the Chapel Royal.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] A third time he was Moderator, 2 August 1643, and was elected a member of the Westminster Assembly of Divines.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] He declined the principalship of St Mary's College, St Andrews, and died unmarried 19 August 1646.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] Next to the Church, Henderson's greatest service was devoted to the University of Edinburgh.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] "He was the ablest educationist and the man of clearest insight of all who had to do with the college since its foundation.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] He saw what was wanted, and had the energy and the tact necessary for securing it.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] It would have been an inestimable advantage for the universities of Scotland if his life could have been prolonged for twenty years " (Grant's Univ. of Edinburgh, i., 209).
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] During the year 1642, the time of the English Civil War, Henderson was employed in managing the correspondence with England respecting ecclesiastical reformation and union.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] He was soon after chosen one of the commissioners appointed to proceed to that country, but was for some time delayed by the civil war.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] Anxious to effect a reconciliation between Charles and his English subjects, he joined with some other leading men in an invitation to the queen to come to Scotland; but this proposition was rejected by the king.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] In 1643 he was, for the third time, chosen moderator of the General Assembly — an occasion which was rendered remarkable by the presence of the English commissioners sent down by the parliament to crave their aid and connsel in the then critical circumstances of both kingdoms.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] During the three following years he remained in London, unremittingly engaged in assisting the Westminster Assembly in preparing the public formularies for the religious union between the three kingdoms.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] A memorable meeting of the General Assembly was held in August 1643.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] Henderson was elected moderator for the third time.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] He presented a draft of the famous Solemn League and Covenant, which was received with great enthusiasm.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] Unlike the National Covenant of 1638, which applied to Scotland only, this document was common to the two kingdoms.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] Henderson, Baillie, Rutherford and others were sent up to London to represent Scotland in the Assembly at Westminster.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] By means of it Henderson has had considerable influence on the history of Great Britain.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] As Scottish commissioner to the Westminster Assembly he was in England from August 1643 till August 1646 and his principal work was the drafting of the Directory for Public Worship.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] Early in 1645 Henderson was sent to the Treaty of Uxbridge to aid the commissioners of the two parliaments in negotiating with the king but nothing came of the conference.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] In 1646 the king joined the Scottish Army; and, after retiring with them to Newcastle-upon-Tyne, he sent for Henderson, and discussed with him the two systems of church government in a number of papers.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] Meanwhile, Henderson was failing in health.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] He sailed to Scotland, and eight days after his arrival died, on 19 August 1646.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] He was buried in Greyfriars Kirkyard, Edinburgh; the grave lies in the southwest section near the Adam mausoleum.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] His death was an occasion of national mourning in Scotland.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] On 7 August Baillie had written that he had heard that Henderson was dying of heartbreak.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] Its foundation was probably certain expressions lamenting Scottish interference in English affairs.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] The failure of this last enterprise was fatal to Henderson's already broken health.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] In June 1645 he had suffered from gravel, and tried the Epsom waters; he now showed symptoms of decline.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] Baillie, on 7 August, wrote that he heard he was 'dying most of heartbreak.' He sailed from Newcastle to Leith, and got home to Edinburgh.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] Here he dined with Sir James Stewart, and was extremely cheerful and hearty, but said, 'there was never a schoolboy more desirous to have the play than I am to have leave of this world.' He made his will on 17 August, and died on 19 August 1646.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] In the beginning of 1645 he was appointed to assist the commissioners of the parliaments of England and Scotland in conducting the treaty between them and the king at Uxbridge.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] On the breaking off of the treaty he returned to London.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] In the spring of 1646, when the king had thrown himself into the hands of the Scottish army, he sent for Mr.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] Henderson, who was considered the most competent person to deal with his majesty in his then circumstances.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] He arrived at Newcastle about the middle of May, and received a welcome reception from the king, but soon perceived that Charles was as unwilling as ever to consent to the establishment of presbyterianism.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] It was agreed that the scruples which the king entertained should be discussed in a series of papers between his majesty and Mr.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] They are eight in number, five by the king, who was assisted by Sir Robert Murray, and three by his reverend opponent.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] Henderson's health being much impaired, he was obliged to remove by sea to Edinburgh, where he died, 19 August 1646, in the 63d year of his age.
[src:disruption-of-1843/alexander-henderson-theologian] His body was interred in the Greyfriars churchyard, where a monument was erected by his nephew to his memory.
[src:disruption-of-1843/ancient-celtic-religion] While the specific deities worshipped varied by region and over time, underlying this were broad similarities in both deities and "a basic religious homogeneity" among the Celtic peoples.
[src:disruption-of-1843/ancient-celtic-religion] Widely worshipped Celtic gods included Lugus, Toutatis, Taranis, Cernunnos, Epona, Maponos, Belenos, and Sucellos.
[src:disruption-of-1843/ancient-celtic-religion] Sacred springs were often associated with Celtic healing deities.
[src:disruption-of-1843/ancient-celtic-religion] Triplicity is a common theme, with a number of deities seen as threefold, for example the Three Mothers.
[src:disruption-of-1843/ancient-celtic-religion] The druids were the priests of Celtic religion, but little is definitively known about them.
[src:disruption-of-1843/ancient-celtic-religion] Greco-Roman writers stated that the Celts held ceremonies in sacred groves and other natural shrines, called nemetons, while some Celtic peoples also built temples or ritual enclosures.
[src:disruption-of-1843/ancient-celtic-religion] Celtic peoples often made votive offerings which would be deposited in water and wetlands, or in ritual shafts and wells.
[src:disruption-of-1843/ancient-celtic-religion] There is evidence that ancient Celtic peoples sacrificed animals, almost always livestock or working animals.
[src:disruption-of-1843/ancient-celtic-religion] There is some evidence that ancient Celts sacrificed humans, and Caesar in his accounts of the Gallic wars claims that the Gauls sacrificed criminals by burning them in a wicker man.
[src:disruption-of-1843/ancient-celtic-religion] Celtic paganism, as practised by the ancient Celts, is a descendant of Proto-Celtic paganism, itself derived from Proto-Indo-European paganism.
[src:disruption-of-1843/ancient-celtic-religion] After the Roman Empire's conquest of Gaul (58–51 BCE) and southern Britain (43 CE), Celtic religion there underwent some Romanization, resulting in a syncretic Gallo-Roman religion with deities such as Lenus Mars, Apollo Grannus, and Telesphorus.
[src:disruption-of-1843/ancient-celtic-religion] The Gauls gradually converted to Christianity from the third century onward.
[src:disruption-of-1843/ancient-celtic-religion] After the end of Roman rule in Britain (c.
[src:disruption-of-1843/ancient-celtic-religion] 410 CE), Celtic paganism began to be replaced by Anglo-Saxon paganism over much of what became England.
[src:disruption-of-1843/ancient-celtic-religion] The Celtic populations of Britain and Ireland gradually converted to Christianity from the fifth century onward.
[src:disruption-of-1843/ancient-celtic-religion] However, Celtic paganism left a legacy in many of the Celtic nations, influenced mythology and in the 20th century served as the basis for a new religious movement, Celtic neopaganism.
[src:disruption-of-1843/ancient-celtic-religion] Some figures from medieval Irish mythology are believed to be versions of earlier deities.
[src:disruption-of-1843/ancient-celtic-religion] According to Miranda Aldhouse-Green, the Celts were also animists, believing that every part of the natural world had a spirit.
[src:disruption-of-1843/ancient-celtic-religion] Various Neopagan groups claim association with Celtic paganism.
[src:disruption-of-1843/ancient-celtic-religion] These groups range from the Reconstructionists, who work to practise ancient Celtic religion with as much accuracy as possible; to New Age, eclectic groups who take some of their inspiration from Celtic mythology and iconography, the most notable of which is Neo-Druidry.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] He was born at Baldovie, on 1 August 1545, the youngest son of Richard Melville of Baldovie, and Geills, daughter of Thomas Abercrombie of Montrose.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] He was educated at the Grammar School, Montrose, and the University of St Andrews.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] He later went to France in 1564, and studied law at Poitiers.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] He became regent in the College of Marceon, and took part in the defence of Poitiers against the Huguenots.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] He then proceeded to Geneva, where he was appointed Professor of Humanity.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] He returned to Scotland in 1574 and was appointed Principal of the University of Glasgow in autumn of that year.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] He did much to establish the University on a proper footing and founded four chairs in Languages, Science and Philosophy.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] He was admitted as minister of Govan in conjunction 13 July 1577.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] Melville was elected Moderator of the General Assembly of the Church of Scotland on 24 April 1578.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] He opposed the Episcopal tendency in the Church, and did much to establish the Presbyterian form of government.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] He further did much to remodel the Scottish Universities, especially St Andrews; St Mary's thereafter being devoted to Divinity, Melville being appointed Principal thereof in November 1580.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] He was again elected Moderator of the General Assembly 24 April and 27 June 1582, and 20 June 1587.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] In the Assembly of October 1581, he took an active part in the libel against Robert Montgomery, Bishop of Glasgow, for simoniacal practices.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] Melville was appointed on a commission to wait upon James VI in 1582, with a remonstrance and petition which, notwithstanding the entreaties of his friends, he presented.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] On 15 February 1584 he was summoned before the Privy Council for alleged treason in a sermon preached at St Andrews the June previous, and ordered to be imprisoned at Blackness, but his friends assisted him to escape to England.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] On Arran's fall he returned to Scotland and was restored by Parliament at Linlithgow in December 1585.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] In 1590 he became rector of the University of St Andrews, which office he held until 1597, and at the coronation of the Queen, 17 May 1590, he recited a Latin poem, the Stephaniskion.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] He was again appointed Moderator of the General Assembly, 7 May 1594, but on a visitation of the University by the King in June 1597, he was deprived of his rectorship.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] He attended the General Assembly at Dundee, March 1598, but was ordered to withdraw by the King.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] In 1599 he was appointed Dean of the Faculty of Theology.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] He caused the Synod of Fife in 1599 to censure certain propositions in the Basilikon Doron by the King.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] At the Assembly at Montrose in March 1600 he unsuccessfully claimed his right to sit, but was successful in that at Burntisland May 1601.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] He took part in that held at Aberdeen in 1605 and offered, with others, a protest to Parliament at Perth in 1606 in favour of the right of free Assembly.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] For this he was summoned with others to London, where he was cited before the English Privy Council for writing a bitter Latin epigram against the accessories of Anglican worship and placed under the custody of John Overal, D.D., Dean of St Paul's, and afterwards of Bilson, Bishop of Winchester.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] Again brought before the Privy Council, he broke into a violent tirade against that Court and was committed to solitary confinement in the Tower.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] Henri de la Tour, Duke de Bouillon, having obtained his release, appointed him to the Chair of Biblical Theology in the University of Sedan, and Melville embarked for France 19 April 1611.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] He died unmarried after a series of illnesses at Sedan in 1622.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] He was born on 1 August 1545 at Baldovie near Montrose, Angus, the youngest son of Richard Melville (brother to Melville of Dysart).
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] Andrew was the youngest of nine sons of Richard Melville of Baldovy, near Montrose, where he was born 1 August 1545.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] At an early age Melville began to show a taste for learning, and his brother did everything in his power to give him the best education.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] In 1564, at nineteen years of age, he set out for France to complete his education at the University of Paris.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] Andrews, he repaired to France in the autumn of 1564, reaching Paris from Dieppe after a roundabout and stormy voyage.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] He now attained great fluency in Greek, made acquirements in oriental languages, studied mathematics and law, and came under the direct influence of Peter Ramus, whose new methods of teaching he subsequently transplanted to Scotland.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] He also attended the last course of lectures delivered by Adrianus Turnebus, professor of Greek, as well as those of Petrus Ramus, whose philosophical method and plan of teaching Melville later introduced into the universities of Scotland.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] It was also in Paris where Melville studied Hebrew under Jean Mercier, one of the leading hebraists of that time.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] From Paris he went to Poitiers (1566) to study civil law, and though only twenty-one was apparently at once made a regent in the college of St Marceon.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] After three years, however, political troubles compelled him to leave France, and he went to Geneva, where he was welcomed by Theodore Beza, at whose instigation he was appointed to the chair of humanity in the academy of Geneva.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] In addition to teaching, Melville continued to study Oriental literature, and in particular acquired from Cornelius Bertram, one of his brother professors, a knowledge of Syriac.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] At Geneva as early as 1572 he met Joseph Scaliger and Francis Hottoman, who in 1572, after the massacre on St.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] Bartholomew's day, took up their abode in that city.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] While he lived at Geneva the massacre of St Bartholomew in 1572 drove immense numbers of Protestant refugees to that city, including several of the most distinguished French men of letters of the time.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] Among these were several men learned in civil law, and political science, and associating with them increased Melville's knowledge and enlarged his ideas of civil and ecclesiastical liberty.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] In 1574 Melville returned to Scotland, and almost immediately received the appointment of Principal of the University of Glasgow, and began its renewal.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] Besides his duties in the university, he officiated as minister of the church of Govan, in the vicinity.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] Melville set himself to establish a good educational system.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] He enlarged the curriculum, and established chairs in languages, science, philosophy and divinity, which were confirmed by charter in 1577.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] His fame spread, and students flocked from all parts of Scotland and beyond.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] He assisted in the reconstruction of the University of Aberdeen in 1575, and to do for St Andrews what he had done for Glasgow, he was appointed Principal of St Mary's College, St Andrews, in 1580.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] His duties there comprised the teaching of theology, Hebrew, Chaldee, Syriac and Rabbinical languages.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] Sir", said Melville, "threaten your courtiers after that manner!
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] It is the same to me whether I rot in the air, or in the ground.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] I have been ready to give up my life where it would not have been half so well wared, at the pleasure of my God.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] I have lived out of your country ten years, as well as in it.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] Let God be glorified, it will not be in your power to hang or exile his truth." This bold language Morton did not venture to resent.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] Melville created a fashion for the study of Greek literature.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] The reforms, however, which his new modes of teaching involved, and even some of his new doctrines, such as the non-infallibility of Aristotle, brought him into conflict with other teachers in the university.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] Melville was moderator of the General Assembly which met at Edinburgh 24 April 1578, in which the second Book of Discipline was approved of.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] The attention of the Assembly was about this time directed to the reformation and improvement of the universities, and Melville was, in December 1580, removed from Glasgow, and installed principal of St.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] Here, besides giving lectures in divinity, he taught the Hebrew, Chaldee, Syriac, and Rabbinical languages, and his prelections were attended, not only by young students in unusual numbers, but also by some of the masters of the other colleges.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] He was moderator of the Assembly which met at St.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] Andrews on 24 April 1582, and also of an extraordinary meeting of the Assembly, convened at Edinburgh on 27 June thereafter, in consequence of the arbitrary measures of the court, in relation particularly to the case of Robert Montgomery, the excommunicated Archbishop of Glasgow.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] He opened the proceedings with a sermon, in which he boldly inveighed against the absolute authority claimed by the government in ecclesiastical matters.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] A spirited remonstrance being agreed to by the Assembly, Melville and others were appointed to present it to the king, then with the court at Perth.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] When the remonstrance was read before his majesty in council, the king's unworthy favourite, the earl of Arran, menacingly exclaimed, "Who dare subscribe these treasonable articles?" "We dare", said the undaunted Melville, and taking a pen, immediately signed his name.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] His example was followed by the other commissioners, and so much were Lennox and Arran over-awed by their intrepidity, that they dismissed them peaceably.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] For about three years Melville had preached, assisted by his nephew, in the parish church of St.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] At his appearance, he denied using these words, entered into a full defence of those he had actually used, and presented a protest and declinature, claiming to be tried by the ecclesiastical court.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] When brought before the king and council, he boldly told them that they had exceeded their jurisdiction in judging of the doctrine, or calling to account any of the ambassadors or messengers of a king and council greater than they, and far above them.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] Then loosing a little Hebrew bible from his belt, and throwing it on the table before them, he said, "That you may see your weakness, oversight, and rashness, in taking upon you that which neither you ought nor can do, there are my instructions and warrant.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] Before, however, being charged to enter himself in ward, his place of confinement was ordered to be changed to Blackness Castle, which was kept by a dependant of Arran.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] While at dinner the king's macer was admitted and gave him the charge to enter within 24 hours: but he avoided being sent there by secretly withdrawing from Edinburgh.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] After staying some time at Berwick, he proceeded to London, and in the ensuing July visited the universities of Oxford and Cambridge, at both of which he was received in a manner becoming his learning and reputation.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] He returned to Scotland in November 1585 after an absence of twenty months, and in March 1586 resumed his lectures in St Andrews, where he continued for twenty years; he became rector of the University in 1590.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] On the disgrace of the earl of Arran, Melville returned to Scotland with the banished lords, in November 1585.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] Having assisted in re-organising the college of Glasgow, he resumed, in the following March, his duties at St.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] The synod of Fife, which met in April, proceeded to excommunicate Patrick Adamson, Archbishop of St.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] Andrews, for his attempts to overturn the presbyterian form of government in the church; and, in return, that prelate issued a sentence of excommunication against Melville, and his nephew, James Melville, with others of their brethren.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] In consequence of this difference with the archbishop, Melville received a written mandate from the king to confine his residence to the north of the Tay, and he was not restored to his office in the university till the following August.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] Some time after, when Adamson had been deprived of his archbishopric, and was reduced to great poverty, finding himself deserted by the king, he addressed a letter to his former antagonist, Melville, expressing regret for his past conduct, and soliciting his assistance.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] Melville hastened to visit him, and not only procured contributions for his relief among his friends, but continued for several months to support him from his own resources.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] In June 1587, Melville was again elected moderator of the Assembly, and nominated one of the commissioners for attending to the proceedings in parliament.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] He was present at the coronation of the queen, 17 May 1590, and recited a Latin poem composed for the occasion, which was immediately published at the desire of the king.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] In the same year he was elected rector of the university of St.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] Andrews, an office which, for a series of years, he continued to hold by re-election.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] In May 1594 he was again elected moderator of the Assembly.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] Shortly after, he appeared on behalf of the church before the lords of the articles, and urged the forfeiture of the popish lords, and along with his nephew and two other ministers, he accompanied the king, at his express request, on his expedition against them.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] In October 1594 he was with the king at Huntly Castle and argued for its demolition.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] In the following year, when it was proposed to recall the popish nobles from exile, he went with some other ministers to the convention of estates at St.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] Andrews, to remonstrate against the design, but was ordered by the king to withdraw, which he did, after a most resolute reply.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] The commission of the Assembly having met at Cupar in Fife, they sent Melville and some other members to expostulate with the king.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] The king listened patiently to this bold admonition, and dismissed them with many fair promises which he never intended to fulfil.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] During the whole time he protected the liberties of the Scottish Church against all encroachments of the government.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] That in the main he was fighting for the constitutionally guaranteed rights of the Church is generally accepted.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] The chief charge against Melville is that his fervour often led him to forget the reverence due to an "anointed monarch".
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] His nephew James Melville, who was present, records the famous statement he made in Falkland in private to King James VI of Scotland, later to become King James I of England.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] In 1599 he was deprived of the rectorship, but was made dean of the faculty of theology.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] The close of Melville's career in Scotland was at length brought about by James in characteristic fashion.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] In May 1606, Melville, with his nephew, and six of their brethren, were called to London by a letter from the king, on the specious pretext that his majesty wished to consult them as to the affairs of the church.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] Soon after their arrival they attended the famous conference held on 23 September, in presence of the king at Hampton Court, at which Melville spoke at great length, and with a boldness which astonished the English nobility and clergy.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] Being by them found guilty of "scandalum magnatum," he was committed first to the custody of the dean of St.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] Paul's, and afterwards to the charge of the bishop of Winchester; but was ultimately sent to the Tower, where he remained a prisoner for four years.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] Cur stant clausi Anglis libri duo regia in ara, Lumina casca duo, pollubra sicca duo?
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] Num sensum cultumque Dei tenet Anglia clausum, Lumine exca suo, sorde sepulta sua?
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] Romano an ritu, dum regalem instruit aram, Purpuream pingit religiosa lupam ?
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] Why stand there on the altar high Two closed books, blind lights, two basins dry?
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] Doth England hold God's mind and worship close.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] Blind of her sight, and buried in her dross?
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] Doth she, with chapel put in Romish dress, The purple whore religiously express?
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] At first he was treated with the utmost rigour, and denied even the use of pen, ink, and paper; but his spirit remained unsubdued, and he beguiled his solitary hours by composing Latin verses, which, with the tongue of his shoe buckle, he engraved on his prison walls.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] By the interference of some friends at court, his confinement was, after the lapse of nearly ten months, rendered less severe.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] About the end of 1607 the Protestants of Rochelle endeavoured to obtain his services as professor of divinity in their college, but the king would not consent to his liberation.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] On being freed, but refused permission to return to his own country, he was invited to fill a professor's chair in the Academy of Sedan, and there he spent the last eleven years of his life.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] M'Crie, says that Andrew Melville "was the first Scotsman who added a taste for elegant literature to an extensive acquaintance with theology." Although he sustained a conspicuous part in all the important public transactions of his time, he neither was nor affected to be the leader of a party.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] In private he was an agreeable companion, remarkable for his cheerfulness and kindliness of disposition.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] Beyond the statement that he was of low stature there is no description of his personal appearance extant, nor is there any known portrait of him.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] The greater part of his writings consists of Latin poems.
[src:disruption-of-1843/andrew-melville] M'Crie, whose Life of Andrew Melville was published in 1824, in 2 volumes, has given the names of all his works, printed and left in manuscript, and there is none of any great extent among them.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] The **Disruption of 1843**, also known as the **Great Disruption**, was a schism in 1843 in which 450 evangelical ministers broke away from the Church of Scotland to form the Free Church of Scotland.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] The main conflict was over whether the Church of Scotland or the British Government had the power to control clerical positions and benefits.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] The Disruption came at the end of a bitter conflict within the Church of Scotland, and had major effects in the church and upon Scottish civic life.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] The Church of Scotland was recognised by Acts of the Parliament as the national church of the Scottish people.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] Particularly under John Knox and later Andrew Melville, the Church of Scotland had always claimed an inherent right to exercise independent spiritual jurisdiction over its own affairs.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] To some extent, this right was recognised by the Claim of Right of 1689, which ended royal and parliamentary interference in the order and worship of the church.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] It was ratified by the Act of Union in 1707.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] On the other hand, the right of patronage, in which the patron of a parish had the right to install a minister of his choice, became a point of contention.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] Many church members believed that this right infringed on the spiritual independence of the church.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] Others felt that this right was a property of the state.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] As early as 1712 the right of patronage had been restored in Scotland, amid remonstrances from the church.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] For many years afterwards, the church's General Assembly tried to reform this practice.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] However the dominant Moderate Party in the church blocked reform out of fear of conflict with the British Government.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] In 1834, the evangelical party attained a majority in the General Assembly for the first time in 100 years.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] One of their actions was to pass the Veto Act, which gave parishioners the right to reject a minister nominated by their patron.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] The Veto Act was to prevent the intrusion of ministers on unwilling parishioners, and to restore the importance of the congregational "call".
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] However, it served to polarise positions in the church, and set it on a collision course with the government.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] The first test of the Veto Act came with the *Auchterarder* case of 1834.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] The parish of Auchterarder unanimously rejected the patron's nominee – and the Presbytery refused to proceed with his ordination and induction.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] The nominee, Robert Young, appealed to the Court of Session.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] In 1838, by an 8–5 majority, the court held that in passing the Veto Act, the church had acted *ultra vires*, and had infringed the statutory rights of patrons.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] It also ruled Church of Scotland was a creation of the state and derived its legitimacy from act of Parliament.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] The*Auchterarder* ruling contradicted the Scottish church's Confession of Faith.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] As Burleigh puts it: "The notion of the Church as an independent community governed by its own officers and capable of entering into a compact with the state was repudiated" (p.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] An appeal to the House of Lords was rejected.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] In a second case, the Court of Session summoned the Presbytery of Dunkeld for proceeding with an ordination despite a court interdict.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] In 1839, the General Assembly suspended seven ministers from Strathbogie for proceeding with an induction in Marnoch in defiance of its orders.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] In 1841, the seven Strathbogie ministers were deposed for acknowledging the superiority of the secular court in spiritual matters.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] The evangelical party later presented to parliament a *Claim, Declaration and Protest Anent the Encroachments of the Court of Session*.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] The claim recognised the jurisdiction of the civil courts over the endowments that the government gave to the Scottish church.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] This "The Claim of Right" was drawn up by Alexander Murray Dunlop.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] However, the claim resolved that the church give up these endowments rather than see the 'Crown Rights of the Redeemer' (i.e. the spiritual independence of the church) compromised.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] This claim was rejected by parliament in January 1843, leading to the Disruption in May.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] On 18 May 1843, 121 ministers and 73 elders led by David Welsh met at the Church of St Andrew in George Street, Edinburgh.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] After Welsh read a Protest, the group left St.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] Andrews and walked down the hill to the Tanfield Hall at Canonmills.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] There they held the first meeting of the Free Church of Scotland, the Disruption Assembly.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] Thomas Chalmers was appointed the first Moderator.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] On 23 May, a second meeting was held for the signing of the Act of Separation by the ministers.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] Eventually, 474 of about 1,200 ministers left the Church of Scotland for the Free Church.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] In leaving the established church, however, they did not reject the principle of establishment.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] As Chalmers declared: "Though we quit the Establishment, we go out on the Establishment principle; we quit a vitiated Establishment but would rejoice in returning to a pure one.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] Perhaps a third of the evangelicals, the "middle party", remained within the established church – wishing to preserve its unity.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] However, for those who left, the issue was clear.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] It was not the democratising of the church (although concern with power for ordinary people was a movement sweeping Europe at the time), but whether the Church was sovereign within its own domain.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] The body of the church reflecting Jesus Christ, not the monarch nor Parliament, was to be its head.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] The Disruption was basically a spiritual phenomenon – and for its proponents it stood in a direct line with the Reformation and the National Covenants.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] Splitting the church had major implications.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] Those who left forfeited livings, manses and pulpits, and had, without the aid of the establishment, to found and finance a national church from scratch.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] This was done with remarkable energy, zeal and sacrifice.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] Another implication was that the church they left was more tolerant of a wider range of doctrinal views.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] There was also the issue of needing to train its clergy, resulting in the establishment of New College, with Chalmers appointed as its first principal.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] It was founded as an institution to educate future ministers and the Scottish leadership, who would in turn guide the moral and religious lives of the Scottish people.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] New College opened its doors to 168 students in November 1843, including about 100 students who had begun their theological studies before the Disruption.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] Most of the principles on which the protestors went out were conceded by Parliament by 1929, clearing the way for the re-union of that year, but the Church of Scotland never fully regained its position after the division.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] The painter David Octavius Hill was present at the Disruption Assembly and decided to record the scene.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] He received encouragement from another spectator, the physicist Sir David Brewster who suggested using the new invention, photography, to get likenesses of all the ministers present, and introduced Hill to the photographer Robert Adamson.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] Subsequently, a series of photographs were taken of those who had been present, and the 5-foot × 11-foot 4 inches (1.53 m × 3.45 m) painting was eventually completed in 1866.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] The partnership that developed between Hill and Adamson pioneered the art of photography in Scotland.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] The painting predominantly features the ministers involved in the Disruption but Hill also included many other men – and some women – who were involved in the establishment of the Free Church.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] The painting depicts 457 people of the 1500 or so who were present at the assembly on 23 May 1843.
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] The social tensions underlying the Disruption are the subject of William Alexander's novel, *Johnny Gibb of Gushetneuk* (1870).
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] David Octavius Hill's use of photography to record the ministers who participated in the schism of 1843 features in Ali Bacon's novel *In the Blink of an Eye* (2018).
[src:disruption-of-1843/disruption-of-1843] The novel *Clear* (2024) by Carys Davies is set against the backdrop of the Great Disruption and the Highland Clearances.
